{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500151"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:09:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:09:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1616"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1616","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1616"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.44,0.02,0.45,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1616"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109488"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1616","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1616"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1616"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91855"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"9127"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3483"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3525"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39079"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109488"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 80-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of lower abdominal pain. She describes the pain as being well-localised to her left iliac fossa, with no significant radiation. During this time she has had some diarrhoea. Over the last two days she has experienced episodes of fever. She has a medical history of atrial fibrillation, diverticular disease and a urinary tract infection one year ago. Her medications include apixaban.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her pulse rate is 125/min, blood pressure 147/94 mmHg, temperature 38.4\u00b0C, respiratory rate 18/min and SpO2 99% on room air. A CT scan is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Retroperitoneal haematoma","Pericolic abscess","E. coli urinary tract infection","Colovesical fistula","Carcinoma of the rectum"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis CT scan demonstrates a large fluid and gas-filled collection (Image) (arrow A) behind the bladder  and immediately anterior to the rectum (Image) (arrow B). This is almost certainly a \u003Cstrong\u003Epericolic abscess\u003C/strong\u003E, formed after an episode of diverticulitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eretroperitoneal haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E would demonstrate a hypodense fluid collection in the retroperitoneal space (i.e. behind the kidneys/closer to the spine). While this patient is on anticoagulation for her AF, and this may cause her to form a haematoma, her fever and the palpable tender mass in her LIF make this unlikely as the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EE. coli\u003C/em\u003E urinary tract infection\u003C/strong\u003E would be unlikely to demonstrate a fluid and gas-filled collection in the pelvis. Such infections would be more likely associated with gas in the urinary bladder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E colovesical fistula\u003C/strong\u003E is a communication between the lumen of the colon and bladder, either via direct communication or via an intermediary abscess. These commonly occur as complications of diverticulitis, although present with pneumaturia, faecaluria or recurrent UTIs. They most often demonstrate gas within the bladder on CT. In this case, there is no gas in the bladder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA complication of\u003Cstrong\u003E carcinoma of the rectum\u003C/strong\u003E could explain this clinical picture, but this would be unusual and such pelvic abscesses are more usually associated with diverticulitis. Furthermore, a CT would almost certainly demonstrate a discrete mass in the the rectum, with possible localised lymphadenopathy or metastatic disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pericolic abscesses are most commonly secondary to complicated diverticular disease."],"references":["Jacobs DO. Clinical practice. Diverticulitis. N Engl J Med. 2007;357(20):2057-66. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18003962/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91855"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1616"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15301"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21960"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15301"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5aaa8e5a-ccaa-4f27-ae3f-6c8ad9e0d213.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5aaa8e5a-ccaa-4f27-ae3f-6c8ad9e0d213.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":783,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"21960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21960"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/sOYqJYT74z1BYa7YfyMHLCdlbt4zYe.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/sOYqJYT74z1BYa7YfyMHLCdlbt4zYe.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":783,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91855","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91855"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-21T20:19:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-21T20:20:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1616"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109488"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type